  "color_desc": {
    "kicker": "The color · in plain words",
    "title_html": "What you're <em>looking</em> at.",
    "prose_paragraphs": [
      "Glacier is the kind of gray you choose when you want the roof to recede and the rest of the house to lead. Not quite black, not quite slate. It is a confident, anchored color that absorbs the eye instead of bouncing it. On a south-facing Florida elevation it reads cool and slightly blue. On a north-facing roof in shade it pulls toward true black.",
      "Up close you can pick out three or four granule shades layered into the surface. From the street they collapse into one mid-dark gray, but the layering is why a quality asphalt roof catches light the way single-color metal never quite does.",
      "Pairs cleanly with white, cream, navy, sage, and warm terra-cotta sidings. Almost any house color works underneath it."
    ],
